Known bugs and fragile areas.

- Metal uses a single shared stride for all buffers, derived from one store
  buffer's row_bytes.  If two pixel buffers had different pixel strides,
  Metal would address one of them incorrectly.  The interpreter and JITs
  handle per-buffer row_bytes independently.

- x86 JIT still shims the new (w, h) entry into the old (n, w) convention
  internally (IMUL+DIV).  Works but wastes a division per call.

- No test coverage for l>0 with deref'd buffers that have row_bytes>0.
  The regression tests only exercise direct (non-deref) pixel buffers.

